{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17489439","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17489439"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T04:16:42+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T04:16:42+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"661"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"661","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/661"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.26,0.27,0.36,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"661"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107092"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"661","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/661"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"661"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89556"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"134"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"8118"},{"type":"tags","id":"9101"},{"type":"tags","id":"9317"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"12911"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2999"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3087"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14527"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36029"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42124"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43805"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107092","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/107092"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA previously well 43-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a four hour history of sudden onset and rapidly increasing upper abdominal pain. The pain is constant, gnawing in nature and worsened when he breathes in deeply. Over the last month he has experienced episodes of upper abdominal pain several hours after meals, but the pain has not been as severe as it is now. He also has chronic back pain but this has not altered recently. He denies other symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he is sweaty and looks distressed. His blood pressure is 108/65mmHg, pulse rate 110/min and temperature 37.2\u003Csup\u003Eo\u003C/sup\u003EC. There is upper abdominal guarding and rigidity.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following investigations will be of most value in establishing the diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Electrocardiogram","Serum lipase","Upper abdominal ultrasound","Erect chest X-ray","Abdominal X-ray"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis picture - constant epigastric pain, worsened by deep breathing - is consistent with peptic ulcer disease. The history of recent upper abdominal pain occurring several hours after meals would also support this diagnosis. Furthermore, a perforation may account for the rapid increase in symptoms and his vital signs suggest he is unstable. Chronic back pain may also suggest NSAID use which could cause the ulcer but this consideration is not necessary to making the diagnosis. The clinical finding of abdominal wall rigidity is very suggestive of perforation or a severe inflammatory process in contact with the parietal peritoneum. In this case the concern must be for perforation and an \u003Cstrong\u003Eerect chest X-ray \u003C/strong\u003Ecan usually be performed very quickly and will be useful to visualise any free air under the diaphragm.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EEpigastric pain has many possible aetiologies. An inferior myocardial infarction is possible and \u003Cstrong\u003EECG\u003C/strong\u003E would be crucial; however, this is very atypical cardiac pain and would not be the most important investigation to establish the diagnosis. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESerum lipase\u003C/strong\u003E would be of use for a pancreatitis diagnosis; however, the pain does not radiate to the back, and there is no alcohol/gallstone history given. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Eultrasound\u003C/strong\u003E would be useful for biliary colic; however, this is an intermittent pain and this is not the typical patient demographic. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Eabdominal X-ray \u003C/strong\u003Ecould be useful for bowel obstruction or other pathologies but this is not most likely.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["An erect chest X-ray is the choice investigation for suspected perforated ulcer"],"references":["Chung KT, Shelat VG. Perforated peptic ulcer - an update. World J Gastrointest Surg. 2017; 9(1): 1-12. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC5237817/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89556"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"661"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89556","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/89556"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-25T08:03:46+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-25T08:03:46+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"661"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107092"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"d